LUMPY SKIN DISEASE - EUROPE (22): BOVINE, UPDATED SITUATION
***********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 24 Aug 2016
Source: Romania's National Sanitary Veterinary & Food Safety Authority, press release [in Romanian, mach. transl., edited]
http://www.ansvsa.ro/?pag=47&id_t=96&id_d=52994


Situation of lumpy skin disease [LSD] in Europe, 1 Jan 2016 to 23 Aug 2016
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Since the beginning of the year, the situation as of 23 Aug 2016 is as follows:

Albania: 7 outbreaks, sporadic vaccination.
Bulgaria: 216 outbreaks, vaccination completed in July 2016.
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia: 100 outbreaks, ongoing vaccination.
Kosovo: 12 outbreaks, sporadic vaccination.
Montenegro: 62 outbreaks, sporadic vaccination.
Serbia: 218 outbreaks, entire country vaccination.
Turkey: 78 outbreaks, vaccination restricted to areas where the disease progresses.
Greece: 95 outbreaks, vaccination.
Russia: 235 outbreaks, the disease approaches the NE border of Ukraine; vaccination ongoing.
Croatia: No outbreaks, but vaccination, triggered by the regional situation, has started on 8 Aug 2016 in the areas Osijek-Baranja, Vucuvar-Srjem, Brod-Posavina, Split-Dalmatia and Dubrovnik-Neretova, to create a buffer zone on the borders with infected countries.

Following the measures taken by the authorities in Zagreb, Croatia cannot trade or move animals outside the vaccinated areas. Thus, live bovine animals, wild ruminants bred in captivity, semen, embryos and ova from vaccinated animals are not allowed to leave the area in which they are held.

Also, fresh meat and meat products from vaccinated animals in Croatia, colostrum, fresh milk, unprocessed skins will be placed on the market outside the vaccination area only if certain conditions aimed at preventing the spread of disease are applied.

--
Communicated by:
Sabine Zentis
